<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n35259a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n35" href="#n35259a">N35 (VI.B.24)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n35all.htm#n35259a"> 259(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Elizabeth Glo-/verina (1762)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">To aid this ridicule the performers in Midas had their names Italianized, so that Pat Mahony and Elizabeth Glover became Signer Patrico Mahoni and Signora Elizabetta Gloverina. As the piece was rich with topical allusions and local satires, and was excessively humorous, it obtained immediate success and long remained popular. <br>As early as March (1762) Barry and Mossop fixed their benefits for the same evening, each announcing that he would play Othello. Mossop relied on his novelty, and Barry on his reputation in that part, to draw large houses. <small> J. Fitzgerald Molloy, <a name="JFMR2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JFMR2"><cite title="source">The Romance of the Irish Stage</cite></a> (1897) 148</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
